    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-09-06T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-09-06T05:00:00-05:00" n="207"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d207">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/15340: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dooman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-06T19:00:00+09:00"
                            >September 6, 1939—7 [<hi rend="italic">5</hi>] p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 6—11:08 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>459. Our 458, September 5, 7 p.m.<note n="6" xml:id="d207fn6">
                        <ref target="frus1931-41v02#pg_9">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 9</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>1. There is quoted in the telegram immediately following<note n="7"
                        xml:id="d207fn7">No. 460, September 6, 7 p.m. (not printed); in this
                        telegram, the Chargé in Japan quoted the British Ambassador’s telegram
                        suggesting that his Government inform the Japanese Government of its
                        intention to retain its troops and ships in the Far East as long as needed
                        to protect British interests and that it was anxious to continue efforts to
                        settle differences with Japan by friendly negotiations
                        (793.94/15348).</note> the text of a telegram which the British Ambassador
                    despatched today to London suggesting in outline the reply which should be sent
                    to the Japanese Government’s note quoted in our telegram under reference. The
                    French Ambassador is telegraphing in substantially similar terms to his
                    Government.</p>
                <p>[For paraphrase of remainder of telegram No. 459, see <ref
                        target="frus1931-41v02#pg_10">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, volume II, page
                        10</ref>.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dooman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
